<HEADLINE>
<P>
MEL BLANC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Laughter is a return to childhood. We forget those who take us there. 
</P>
<P>
Today I learned of Mel Blanc's death and remembered how for four years I was 
chauffeuring him from his home in Pacific Palisades to the Hanna Barbera 
Studios for some dubbing. 
</P>
<P>
As we drove down Sunset, I told Mel, weakened by emphysema and forced to 
breathe with the aid of a portable oxygen machine, how much I had loved Bugs 
Bunny and Daffy Duck as a boy, but how I had always got Elmer Fudd confused 
with Porky Pig. 
</P>
<P>
We stopped for a traffic light. Mel removed the nostril clip from his oxygen 
tube and turning, began reciting the litany of voices we love him for -- Bugs, 
Daffy, Tweety, Sylvester, Yosemite Sam, Road Runner, the Flintstones and many 
others. 
</P>
<P>
Inside an idling Rolls-Royce in the next lane, two elegant ladies gaped at the 
elderly man going through his vocal imitations and the appreciative driver 
laughing as he listened. 
</P>
<P>
That's why it saddened me to learn, "Th-th-at-'s all, folks." 
</P>
<P>
STEWART LINDH 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
