<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA WANTS CITY, COUNTY PLANS INTEGRATED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE PADILLA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Santa Clarita City Council, eager to have a greater voice in planning for 
the entire Santa Clarita Valley, wants to join Los Angeles County officials in 
creating the planning blueprint that will guide expansion in the fast-growing 
valley for the next 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
City Manager George Caravalho said Monday that the city and county should 
coordinate their efforts to draft general plans for the region. At present, 
Santa Clarita and the county's Department of Regional Planning are preparing 
separate plans for virtually the same area. 
</P>
<P>
"They have to be put together and integrated," Caravalho said. General plans 
provide overall guidelines for development, specifying zoning and setting 
development priorities in a region. 
</P>
<P>
The City Council is expected to approve a letter tonight calling on County 
Supervisor Mike Antonovich to direct planning officials to coordinate their 
efforts with Santa Clarita. The county planning department is tentatively 
scheduled to complete a draft general plan for the Santa Clarita Valley next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
City Wants to Catch Up 
</P>
<P>
The city is about two to three months behind the county in drafting its general 
plan. Santa Clarita wants the county to delay its efforts to allow the city to 
catch up, Caravalho said. 
</P>
<P>
Caravalho said the city and county staffs have had informal discussions about 
the county's proposed general plan, but "we do not feel that is adequate." The 
city would prefer a more formal coordination between the two governments, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Caravalho said the city also hopes to learn more about how the county plans to 
process a backlog of 45 general plan amendments that, if approved, would 
provide 38,000 more dwelling units in the Santa Clarita Valley. 
</P>
<P>
The City Council has often expressed interest in developments outside the city 
and has repeatedly said it wishes to annex as much of the surrounding 
unincorporated territory as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072589-0023 </DOCNO>
