<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Israeli government approved a $140-million emergency spending package to 
counter economic stagnation and the worst unemployment in 20 years. Prime 
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Cabinet, meeting in special session, decided that the 
extra funds will be spent mainly on labor-intensive projects and investment in 
industry. Almost 30% of the money will be spent building new roads or upgrading 
existing routes. The Israeli economy has shown no growth in 1989. 
</P>
