<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHRIMPERS FORCE SUSPENSION OF LAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With hundreds of angry shrimpers threatening to renew their blockade of Gulf of 
Mexico ports, Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher agreed Monday to suspend a 
new requirement that shrimp boats be equipped with devices to keep sea turtles 
from becoming ensnared in the nets. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached during an emergency meeting between Mosbacher and Gulf 
Coast congressmen, placed an immediate 45-day moratorium on enforcement of the 
federal law. 
</P>
<P>
Just last Thursday, Mosbacher had ordered that the controversial law be 
enforced after an earlier suspension. 
</P>
<P>
The shrimpers say that the turtle-excluding devices cause them to lose as much 
as 40% of their catch; conservationists say the rule is necessary to save an 
endangered species of sea turtle. 
</P>
<P>
Mosbacher announced the plan after meeting with about two dozen congressmen 
from Gulf states. He said the suspension would allow a "cooling-off period." 
</P>
</TEXT>
