<HEADLINE>
<P>
CENSORSHIP ENDS AFTER CHIEF CENSOR IS SLAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COLOMBO, Sri Lanka 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The national government lifted press censorship Monday, a day after Sri Lanka's 
chief censor was shot to death by suspected left-wing rebels. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Ranjan Wijeratne announced the move at a meeting with 
editors of Sri Lankan newspapers, a government official said. 
</P>
<P>
Wijeratne asked them not to glorify terrorism and advised them to exercise 
self-censorship in the interests of the country, a journalist present at the 
meeting said. 
</P>
<P>
Censorship was imposed July 5 amid escalating ethnic violence in the island 
nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
