<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOSHIBA GROWTH IN IRVINE PROCEEDING; 
</P>
<P>
TELEPHONE OPERATION TO MOVE FROM JAPAN LATER IN YEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID OLMOS, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As part of a three-year expansion that will double the size of its Orange 
County operations, Toshiba will transfer production of some business telephone 
products from Japan to Irvine later this year. 
</P>
<P>
The move will create just 40 local jobs in October, but Toshiba's plans call 
for boosting its local employment by 850 positions by the end of 1991, said 
Robert A. Wittenberg, a spokesman for Toshiba America Information Systems Inc., 
an Irvine-based unit of Japan's Toshiba Corp. 
</P>
<P>
In an interview last March, Information Systems President Kiichi Hataya 
disclosed a broad plan to expand the company's local operations by moving more 
manufacturing from overseas to Irvine and other Toshiba facilities in the 
United States. On Monday, Toshiba formally announced the latest phase of that 
expansion. The company declined to disclose the size of its investment in the 
expansion. 
</P>
<P>
Beginning Oct. 1, the Information Systems unit will move manufacturing of 
private-branch exchange, or PBX, systems and business telephones from Japan to 
Irvine, Hataya said. 
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the expansion took place in January when Toshiba boosted 
local production of laptop computers and began making cellular mobile 
telephones in Irvine. And in April, it began local production of office 
copiers. 
</P>
<P>
The Information Systems division employs 850 people in Irvine and 1,200 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
Hataya said the move is part of a Toshiba program to manufacture more products 
closer to their markets. 
</P>
<P>
"By producing systems in the United States," Hataya said, "we will be far 
better able to maintain inventory control, respond more efficiently to customer 
needs and react with more immediacy to fluctuations in marketplace demand." 
</P>
<P>
Hataya said the expansion is also part of an effort by Toshiba "to demonstrate 
its commitment to the U.S. marketplace" by purchasing more parts and supplies 
for its U.S.-made products from local suppliers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Toshiba announced another phase in three-year plan to boost Irvine 
employment by 850 jobs. DON KELSEN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
