<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
IBM TO MANAGE KODAK DATA SYSTEM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
International Business Machines Corp. will take over the management of most of 
Eastman Kodak Co.'s data-processing operations, the companies said today. 
</P>
<P>
IBM will manage Kodak's computers from a new data center at Kodak headquarters 
in Rochester, N.Y. The value of the deal for IBM was not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
The arrangement is intended to save money for Kodak, which said Monday that it 
would take a $225 million charge against second-quarter earnings and was 
disappointed with its operating results. 
</P>
<P>
IBM approached Kodak with the proposal, said David E. McDowell, the president 
of IBM's National Service Division. IBM has been trying to lessen its 
dependence on sales of computer hardware and software and instead become a 
"partner" with its customers, embedding itself deeply in their businesses. 
</P>
<P>
The Kodak deal is by far the biggest yet in which IBM actually takes over the 
support for a company's data-processing operation, McDowell said. As such, it 
could lead to other arrangements of similar magnitude. 
</P>
<P>
The partners envision that IBM could eventually take over management of data 
processing at other centers in the United States that are excluded from the 
first phase as well as overseas locations, said Katherine M. Hudson, Kodak's 
director of corporate information systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
